I hope I understand what you try to do. But there is also a solution which does not need the sizeof-Operator. You can define a class and tell the compiler how it should arrange the fields in the memory. One example:

    [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential, Pack = 0)]
    public class YourClass
    {
     public int SomeInteger;
    
     public byte SomeByte;
    
     public long Timestamp;
    }

In this example, the first four bytes will be `SomeInteger`, the next byte will be `SomeByte`, and then will follow 8 bytes for `Timestamp`. How can then easily convert instances of this class into a byte array: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3278827/how-to-convert-a-structure-to-a-byte-array-in-c

Addendum: After reading your last comment, I saw you need a different solution. If you don&#39;t want to serialize the whole object always, you could also use a list instead of a byte array:

